# Riverpod Patterns

## Provider types — when to use each

| Provider | Use for |
|----------|---------|
| `Provider` | Synchronous, side-effect-free values (router, dio, config) |
| `FutureProvider` | One-shot async fetch that can fail |
| `StreamProvider` | Reactive stream (e.g. Drift DAO queries) |
| `NotifierProvider` | Mutable state with methods; replaces `StateNotifierProvider` |
| `AsyncNotifierProvider` | Mutable async state with methods |
| `.family` suffix | Parameterized providers (id-keyed lookups) |

## Examples

```dart
// ✅ Stream from Drift DAO — UI reacts to DB changes automatically
final itemsProvider = StreamProvider<List<Item>>((ref) {
  return ref.watch(databaseProvider).itemDao.watchAll();
});

// ✅ Notifier with a method
class CounterNotifier extends Notifier<int> {
  @override
  int build() => 0;
  void increment() => state++;
}
final counterProvider = NotifierProvider<CounterNotifier, int>(CounterNotifier.new);

// ✅ Family provider
final itemByIdProvider = FutureProvider.family<Item, int>((ref, id) async {
  return ref.watch(itemRepositoryProvider).getById(id);
});

// ❌ Don't use StateProvider for complex state — use Notifier instead
final counterProvider = StateProvider<int>((ref) => 0); // too simple for anything real
```

## Consuming providers in widgets

```dart
class FooScreen extends ConsumerWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context, WidgetRef ref) {
    final items = ref.watch(itemsProvider);
    return items.when2(
      data: (list) => ListView(...),
    );
  }
}
```

## Rules

- Providers live in `presentation/providers/` inside the feature directory.
- Never `ref.read` inside `build()` — use `ref.watch` for reactive data, `ref.read` only inside callbacks.
- Use `AsyncValue.when2()` (defined in `core/utils/async_value_ext.dart`) for consistent loading/error UI.
- After modifying `@riverpod`-annotated code run: `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs`
- Generated `*.g.dart` files are gitignored — never edit them manually.

## Code generation (optional)

If you use `@riverpod` annotation from `riverpod_annotation`, add the `part` directive:

```dart
part 'foo_provider.g.dart';

@riverpod
Future<List<Item>> items(Ref ref) async { ... }
```
